Slide 1 voiceover (1:00)
[Open with a beat of silence. Let the headline read.]

"The single hardest compliance question in this organization is also the simplest one: are we compliant right now. Today, every answer depends on people stitching it together — from email, drives, spreadsheets, the source systems themselves.
Three structural reasons. Evidence is scattered across inboxes, shared drives, ticketing systems. Scope is reasoned, not recorded — every cycle re-litigates the same applicability decisions. And the work is repeated across assessments — RCSA, internal audit, regulatory assessments each reassemble context, ownership, and evidence independently. Same evidence. Recreated each time.
The issue is not a lack of evidence. It's the absence of a consistent way to collect, structure, and trace it across the systems where it originates."

Transition (advance to Slide 2): no verbal bridge needed — the shift speaks for itself.

Slide 2 voiceover (1:00)

"What changes is the shape of evidence itself. We're designing it as a governed record — sourced from connected systems and upstream monitoring platforms, structured into one record that holds the relationships that matter.
Three input modes. Connected source systems, with read-only connectors. Upstream monitoring platforms — continuous control monitoring, for example — whose outputs flow downstream as inputs. And owner-provided artifacts where automation isn't possible."

[Gesture to the right-hand box]

"The platform is designed to structure those inputs into one governed evidence record. It holds the control, application, scope, and evidence relationships. It's designed to route ownership, review, and the decision trail. And to maintain freshness and reuse across assessments."

[Deliver the three-part close clearly, with deliberate pauses on the separators]

"Upstream when present. Direct when required. Always loosely coupled."


Slide 3 voiceover (1:00)

"This is what changes for the organization."

[Gesture to the framework chips along the top]

"These are the assessment domains in scope. RCSA. SARM. Internal audit. COS RCSA. OSFI assessments. NIST assessments. The same evidence model is designed to serve all of them."

[Move to the four cards]

"One evidence model — a single structured record supports risk, audit, and regulatory processes. No duplicate effort — evidence collected once, reused across assessments. Consistent across frameworks — the same control and evidence relationships apply whether the assessment is OSFI, NIST, COS, or internal governance. And operational efficiency — teams spend less time collecting evidence and more time reviewing it and managing risk."


Slide 4 voiceover (0:30)

"The AI layer compounds the platform's value. The principle: AI operates on structured records and decision trails. It assists the people who own the control, the review, and the sign-off."

[Gesture to the four boxes]

"Change review summaries. Reuse suggestions. Anomaly spotting. Assessment query support. Two of these are running today — change review summaries and AI scope classification, which you'll see in a moment. Reuse, anomaly spotting, and assessment query ship through production launch on the same foundation."

[Deliver the closing line clearly — let each phrase land separately]

"People keep the judgment. The platform keeps the record. AI takes the repetition."

[Pause — then transition to demo]

"Let me show you the platform end-to-end. One cycle from source-system sync through cycle close, with AI working at two points."

[Start the pre-recorded video.]

Demo voiceover (6:00 total, 6 segments)
The video plays muted; voiceover lands on top. Don't read these verbatim — hit the beats.
0:00 – 0:30 — Frame + open validated cycle
On screen: EMS app home, navigate to Cycles list, open the validated cycle from this month.

"What I'm showing you is the platform running end-to-end on real source-system data from this month. One complete cycle — from source-system sync through evidence record generation, with AI working at two points along the way. The governed record substrate, the AI layer, the audit trail — all visible in this one cycle."


0:30 – 1:30 — Cycle workflow (the spine)
On screen: Cycle record opens. Show 5 stages complete on the Business Process Flow. Show cycle metadata.

"This is one cycle. The platform runs cycles on a schedule — it pulls fresh data from the controls framework and the application portfolio, processes it through five stages, locks the cycle at close. Every stage has a gate; every gate requires the platform to validate the work before advancing. The cycle on screen completed end-to-end without manual intervention."


1:30 – 2:30 — AI Import Assessment (first AI moment)
On screen: Scroll to the AI Import Assessment field on the Cycle record. Narrative text visible.

"Stage one — the platform syncs from the source systems and AI produces this narrative summary. What changed. What was added, modified, removed. Which controls might be affected. Which applications shifted scope flags.
The Risk Manager opens the cycle and reads the summary — not the raw diffs across two source systems. The AI removes the repetition of reading hundreds of change records. The Risk Manager keeps the judgment about what those changes mean for the compliance posture."


2:30 – 3:30 — AI Scope Classification + applicability (second AI moment)
On screen: Navigate to a Control Procedure record. Show the AI-classified Scope Type. Open the Applicability sub-grid with multiple Applications.

"Stage two — for every new or changed Control Procedure, AI classifies its scope. Common control, application-specific, or hybrid. That classification drives the downstream applicability computation.
For the Control Procedure on screen, the platform has computed which applications it applies to — each row is one application-control pair, with applicability determined by the platform from source-system inputs. Not by a person interpreting a spreadsheet. Same inputs produce the same answer every cycle. Becomes rule-driven through production launch."


3:30 – 4:45 — Evidence record + governed record structure
On screen: Open an Evidence record. Snapshot fields populated. SharePoint link visible. Audit history if surfaced.

"Stage three — for every applicable control-application pair, the platform generates a governed evidence record. The record on screen was produced by the platform; nobody created it manually.
Every record carries a snapshot of what it was attesting to — the control as it was worded at that moment, the application's attributes at that moment, the scope as it stood at that moment. The platform writes that snapshot at generation. Integrity rules locking the snapshot against later modification ship through production launch.
The snapshot is the foundation of the audit trail. The SharePoint link is where the evidence content lives. At production launch, control owners begin uploading actual evidence content into this structure — and the governed record handles the relationships, the ownership, the review trail."


4:45 – 5:30 — Cycle close + locked state
On screen: Navigate back to the cycle. Show closed state, completed indicator.

"Stage four — when the cycle closes, the platform locks its state. The compliance posture as of that cycle is preserved permanently and remains queryable. The next cycle is already in motion against the next source-system sync. The platform is a continuous record-keeper, not a periodic collection project."


5:30 – 6:00 — Close
On screen: Step back to Cycles list showing multiple cycles, or to a posture view if available.

"That's the platform running end-to-end today. Source-system integration. Cycle workflow with audit gates. AI summarization. AI classification. Governed evidence records with snapshot capture. Cycle close with locked state. The rule engine and the expanded AI layer — reuse, anomaly spotting, assessment query — ship through production launch on this foundation."

