Q&A prep
Q: "Is this running today?"

"The platform's foundation is built and validated end-to-end against real source-system data. Operational collection begins at production launch in [QUARTER — fill in]. What you saw in the demo is the platform that's ready to run."

Q: "When is production launch?"

"We're targeting [QUARTER]; final date depends on completing the rule engine and continuous workflow currently in build."

Q: "How does this interact with Archer / LeanIX / [existing system]?"

"The platform integrates as a read-only consumer — the controls framework remains the source of truth in the controls system, the application portfolio remains in the portfolio system. EMS sits between them, producing the governed evidence record."

Q: "Is the AI doing the compliance decisions?"

"No. AI assists the people who own the control, the review, and the sign-off. The change-review AI summarizes what reviewers should look at. The classification AI proposes a scope category; the Risk Manager validates and overrides where needed. People keep the judgment. The platform keeps the record. AI takes the repetition."

Q: "Is the evidence immutable today?"

"The snapshot mechanism is built — every evidence record captures the control, application, and scope as they stood at generation. The platform writes that snapshot on every record. The integrity rules that lock the snapshot against later modification ship through production launch."

Q: "What's the build timeline through production?"

"Rule engine is in build this quarter. Continuous evidence workflow follows. Production launch [QUARTER]. The AI agent layer extends through and beyond production."

Q: "How does the platform handle [specific framework — OSFI, NIST, etc.]?"

"The same governed evidence record structure serves all the frameworks in scope. The control-evidence relationships are mapped once and reused — the platform doesn't recreate evidence for each framework's assessment."


Voiceover discipline (apply during rehearsal)
For every line, ask: is what I'm about to claim actually built today, or am I implying operational state that hasn't been reached?
Phrases to scrub or qualify:

"is collecting" / "are collecting" → "produces" / "generates"
"audit-immutable" → "snapshot captured at generation; integrity rules ship through production launch"
"live" / "in production" / "operational" — only use for things running daily on real audit-bearing data (the bar is high)
"running today" — defensible for: source-system sync, cycle workflow, AI Import Assessment, AI scope classification, applicability computation, evidence record generation (test records, not actual evidence content)

Build-state truth (do not violate):

Source-system sync, cycle workflow, gate validation, applicability computation, evidence generation, confirmation: all built and tested end-to-end on real source-system data
Evidence records: snapshot mechanism built; integrity rule enforcement ships through production launch
Rule engine: in build this quarter, not demo-able
Continuous evidence workflow: not started, not demo-able
AI reuse / anomaly / query agents: under build, not demo-able
Engagements: not started, not demo-able


End of script.
